They say only mad dogs and English(wo)men go out in the midday sun. So, not wanting to break with tradition and having woken late and faffed about for too long that morning, we set off on the 1.5 hr hike from Zebugg to Ramla Bay, Gozo in 35 degree sun üôÑ

After a couple of wrong turns, 2 litres of water, arguments about whose google maps was correct and  mild heatstroke induced stroppy moments, we arrived at the unspoilt sandy bay with crystal clear water lapping against the rocks. 

Known locally as Ramla il-ƒ¶amra‚Äù ‚Äì the ‚ÄòRed Sandy Beach,‚Äô the bay is without a doubt worth the trip (although you can of course get a bus to the nearest village or drive, if walking up steep mountain roads and tripping down even steeper narrow paths sweating off half your body weight in the process really isn‚Äôt really your thing). 

During the time of the Knights of St. John, the beach was fortified to defend Gozo from foreign threats, constructing the Vendome battery in 1715 and a submerged wall to deter invaders from landing on the beach. 

On the cliffs at the western end of the beach is the mythical Calypso‚Äôs Cave - said to have belonged to Calypso, the mythical nymph who shagged Odysseus senseless and offered him eternal life to keep him from returning home for 7 years as described in Homer‚Äôs Odyssey. 
.

node.text:
Tal-Mixta Cave, which we confused with Calypso's cave. It's opposite to it though! So you can still imagine that Calypso used to visit this one as well. 

It is believed here that Calypso's cave is the one which was a place of exile of a nymph Calypso, daughter of Atlas. In Homer's Odyssey, Calypso attempts to keep the fabled Greek hero Odysseus on her island to make him her immortal husband. According to Homer, Calypso kept Odysseus prisoner at Ogygia for seven years. Calypso enchants Odysseus with her singing as she moves to and fro, weaving on her loom with a golden shuttle.

And if you love the Percy Jackson series you might remember when Leo was on Calypso's island! 

. 

.

.

node.text: Today we went to see Calypso‚Äôs Cave in Gozo. Unfortunately it‚Äôs closed for tourists now but we still had a glimpse of the entrance at least. According to the local myth this is the place where Calypso (One of Oceanides sea nymphs, the daughter of the Titan god Atlas and Tethys.) kept Odysseus from returning to Ithaca after the Trojan war. Calypso saved Odysseus from the sea when he was adrift for 9 days after losing his ship. She welcomed him and fell in love with him. She wanted him to be her immortal husband by giving him eternal youth. Odysseus didn‚Äôt accept it because he was still dreaming about going back home to Ithaca and his wife. Calypso was so much in love with him that despite his wishes she hoped he would fall in love with her and kept seducing him. Eventually she succeeded and made him her lover. They stayed together in Calypsos‚Äô beautiful cave home for 7 years before the gods intervened and  convinced her to let Odysseus go. She helped him to build a boat to take him home. She even provided him with enough food and wine for the journey and good winds. #calypso #calypsocave #calypsocaveview #calypsocavegozo #ramlabay #ramlabeach #redsandbeach #gozo #gozoisland #beatifulview #sea #mediterreneansea #mediterrenean #ramlalhamra #sandybeach #azuresea #azurewater #hiking #dayout #beautifulnature #f√∂ldk√∂zitenger #caveentrance #greekmithology #odysseus #odyssey #homer #modernhousewifewithra #tengerpart #mutimerrejarsz #mutimerrej√°rsz

This is a (not very good) oldie from 2014 that I've scanned in. I'm posting it because I've just started a Greek Mythology course and I've been reading about Odysseus and Calypso. I googled the island of Ogygia and it is traditionally believed to be the island of Gozo. The first time I visited Gozo I fell so in love I stayed an extra week. One morning our Airbnb host kindly drove us to Calypso cave which is said to be where Odysseus and Calypso lived, and so I had to dig out this photo. Apparently it's crumbling now and you can't visit which is heartbreaking, glad to have visited this special place when I could! üßø

‚ÄúRound her cave there was a thick wood of alder, poplar, and sweet smelling cypress trees, wherein all kinds of great birds had built their nests- owls, hawks, and chattering sea-crows that occupy their business in the waters. A vine loaded with grapes grew luxuriantly around the mouth of the cave; there were also four running rills of water in channels cut pretty close together, and turned hither and thither so as to irrigate the beds of violets and luscious herbage over which they flowed.‚Äù
This how the island of Ogygia is described, where the beautiful nymph Calypso lived. Some authors recognized this paradisiac place in the island of Gozo, the second largest and inhabited island of Malta. ‚ÄúIt is an island covered with forest, in the very middle of the sea, and a goddess lives there‚Äù.
Although it is difficult to establish with certainty whether Gozo is truly the mythological island of Ogygia, the Maltese (especially the Gozitans) are really proud of it. For sure it is undeniable that Gozo is truly a paradise island. And here is the famous cave where the nymph, according to the myth, lived and where Ulysses was forced to live with her: Calypso Cave. ‚Äú..he was longing to return to his wife and country, was detained by the goddess Calypso, who had got him into a large cave and wanted to marry him. ‚Äú
The cave itself is not that striking but it has a spectacular view and a peculiar atmosphere due to its links with Greek legends. It overlooks the red sandy beach of Ramla Bay. The blue of the sea, the green and thick vegetation that surrounds the beach and its unique red sand, is truly a place that ‚ÄúEven a god could not help being charmed with such a lovely spot‚Äù.
